### Writing Files in Java

Java provides several ways to write data to files.

---

### Using FileWriter

```java
FileWriter fw = new FileWriter("output.txt");    // overwrite
FileWriter fw = new FileWriter("output.txt", true);  // append
fw.write("Hello World");
fw.close();
```

---

### Using BufferedWriter

```java
BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("file.txt"));
bw.write("Line 1");
bw.newLine();
bw.write("Line 2");
bw.close();
```

---

### Using Files (Java NIO)

```java
// Write string
Files.writeString(Paths.get("file.txt"), "content", 
    StandardOpenOption.CREATE, StandardOpenOption.APPEND);

// Write lines
List<String> lines = Arrays.asList("Line 1", "Line 2");
Files.write(Paths.get("file.txt"), lines);

// Write bytes
Files.write(Paths.get("file.dat"), byteArray);
```

---

### Using PrintWriter

```java
PrintWriter pw = new PrintWriter(new FileWriter("file.txt"));
pw.println("Formatted text");
pw.printf("Number: %d", 42);
pw.close();
```

---

### FileOutputStream (Binary)

```java
FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("data.dat");
fos.write(new byte[]{0x48, 0x65, 0x6C});  // Hel
fos.close();
```

> **Key Point:** FileWriter with `true` second argument appends to file. Without it, the file is overwritten. Always close writers or use try-with-resources.

codeExample:
import java.io.*;
import java.nio.file.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        // Method 1: BufferedWriter
        try (BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("output1.txt"))) {
            bw.write("Hello from BufferedWriter");
            bw.newLine();
            bw.write("Second line");
        }

        // Method 2: Files.writeString (Java 11+)
        Files.writeString(Paths.get("output2.txt"), 
            "Hello from Files.writeString");

        // Method 3: Files.write with lines
        List<String> lines = Arrays.asList("Line A", "Line B", "Line C");
        Files.write(Paths.get("output3.txt"), lines);

        // Method 4: Appending
        try (FileWriter fw = new FileWriter("output1.txt", true)) {
            fw.write("\nAppended line");
        }

        System.out.println("Files written successfully");

        // Verify
        System.out.println(Files.readString(Paths.get("output1.txt")));
    }
}
